## Environment Variables

| Variable | Description |
|---|---|
| `AUTH_SECRET` | Random string for NextAuth session encryption |
| `DISCORD_CLIENT_ID` | Discord OAuth2 application client ID |
| `DISCORD_CLIENT_SECRET` | Discord OAuth2 application client secret |
| `DATABASE_TOKEN` | MongoDB connection string (same as bot) |
| `DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN` | Bot token — used to fetch guild channels/roles via Discord REST |
| `NEXTAUTH_URL` | Dashboard URL (e.g. `https://your-app.vercel.app`) |

## Phase 1: Project Bootstrap

1. Create new GitHub repo and scaffold with `npx create-next-app@latest . --typescript --tailwind --app --no-src-dir`
2. Install dependencies listed above
3. `lib/db.ts` — Mongoose singleton connection (reuses `DATABASE_TOKEN`)
4. `models/GuildConfiguration.ts` — TypeScript Mongoose model mirroring the bot's `GuildConfiguration` schema exactly
5. `lib/auth.ts` — NextAuth v4 config with Discord provider (scopes: `identify guilds`), persist `accessToken` in session
6. `app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts` — NextAuth API route handler
7. `middleware.ts` — protect all `/guilds/**` routes; redirect unauthenticated users to `/login`

## Phase 2: Guild Selection

8. `app/login/page.tsx` — Landing page with "Login with Discord" button
9. `lib/discord.ts` — Helper functions using Discord REST API:
   - `getUserGuilds(accessToken)` — `GET /users/@me/guilds` (user's guilds)
   - `getBotGuilds()` — `GET /users/@me/guilds` with bot token (guilds the bot is in)
   - `getGuildChannels(guildId)` — `GET /guilds/{id}/channels` with bot token
   - `getGuildRoles(guildId)` — `GET /guilds/{id}/roles` with bot token
10. `app/guilds/page.tsx` — Lists guilds where user has Administrator AND bot is present; shows "Invite Bot" link for guilds where bot is missing
11. `app/api/guilds/route.ts` — API endpoint backing the guilds page

## Phase 3: Dashboard Layout + Config Pages

12. `app/guilds/[guildId]/layout.tsx` — Sidebar navigation with tabs (Suggestions, XP, Welcome, Mod Log, Minecraft) + guild name/icon
13. `app/guilds/[guildId]/page.tsx` — Overview or redirect to first section

Each config page follows the same pattern:
- Server component loads current config from DB + fetches channels/roles from Discord API
- Passes data to a client `<ConfigForm>` component
- Form uses react-hook-form + Zod validation
- Submits via `fetch()` PATCH to the corresponding API route

### Suggestions

- **Page:** `app/guilds/[guildId]/suggestions/page.tsx`
- **API:** `app/api/guilds/[guildId]/config/suggestions/route.ts`
- **Fields:**
  - `suggestionChannelIds` — multi-select of text channels
  - `suggestionCooldownMs` — number input (0–86400 seconds, stored as ms)

### XP

- **Page:** `app/guilds/[guildId]/xp/page.tsx`
- **API:** `app/api/guilds/[guildId]/config/xp/route.ts`
- **Fields:**
  - `xpIgnoredChannelIds` — multi-select of channels
  - `xpLevelUpChannelId` — single channel select (empty = same channel)
  - `xpDisableLevelUpMessages` — toggle
  - `levelRoles` — array of { level (number), roleId (role select) }, max 20 entries

### Welcome / Goodbye

- **Page:** `app/guilds/[guildId]/welcome/page.tsx`
- **API:** `app/api/guilds/[guildId]/config/welcome/route.ts`
- **Fields:**
  - `welcomeChannelId` — single channel select
  - `welcomeMessage` — textarea with placeholder hints (`{user}`, `{server}`, `{membercount}`)
  - `goodbyeMessage` — textarea with same placeholders
  - `welcomeEmbed` — toggle (embed vs plain text)
  - `welcomeColor` — hex color picker (default: `#00AA00`)
  - `goodbyeColor` — hex color picker (default: `#FF0000`)
  - `autoRoleIds` — multi-select of roles, max 5

### Mod Log

- **Page:** `app/guilds/[guildId]/modlog/page.tsx`
- **API:** `app/api/guilds/[guildId]/config/modlog/route.ts`
- **Fields:**
  - `modLogChannelId` — single channel select

### Minecraft

- **Page:** `app/guilds/[guildId]/minecraft/page.tsx`
- **API:** `app/api/guilds/[guildId]/config/minecraft/route.ts`
- **Fields:**
  - `pingEnabled` — toggle (enable/disable `/minecraft` command)
  - `mcServers` — CRUD list (max 10 servers per guild):
    - `name` — text input (lowercase, 1–32 chars, regex: `/^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9_-]{0,31}$/`)
    - `ip` — text input (hostname/IP with optional port 1–65535)
    - `alertChannelId` — single channel select
    - `alertRoleId` — single role select (requires alertChannelId set first)
    - `alertPingMode` — select: `both` | `online` | `offline`
    - `liveEmbedChannelId` — single channel select (read-only display; managing live embeds is done via bot commands)
    - `liveEmbedMode` — select: `edit` | `resend` (read-only display)
  - **Read-only fields** (displayed but not editable): `lastOnlineStatus`, `peakPlayersToday`, `peakPlayersDate`, `liveEmbedMessageId`

## Phase 4: Security & Validation

14. `lib/validateAdmin.ts` — Shared helper called by every PATCH API route:
    - Verifies the authenticated user has `ADMINISTRATOR` permission (bit `0x8`) on the target guild
    - Uses Discord REST: `GET /guilds/{id}/member/{userId}` or checks permissions from the guilds list
    - Returns 403 if unauthorized
15. `lib/schemas.ts` — Zod schemas per config section, mirroring bot-side validation:
    - Minecraft: server name regex, IP format, port range 1–65535, max 10 servers
    - Suggestions: cooldown 0–86400000ms
    - XP: max 20 level roles
    - Welcome: max 5 auto-roles, color as valid hex number
16. All `PATCH` API routes: `validateAdmin()` → Zod `.parse(body)` → `findOneAndUpdate()` → return saved config

## Phase 5: Deployment

17. Push repo to GitHub
18. Create Vercel project → connect to the GitHub repo (root directory: `/`)
19. Set environment variables on Vercel (see table above)
20. In Discord Developer Portal → OAuth2 → Add redirect URI: `https://<vercel-domain>/api/auth/callback/discord`

## Bot-Side Impact

- **None.** The dashboard writes directly to MongoDB. The bot's in-memory guild config cache (`guildConfigCache.js`) has a 60-second TTL — changes made via the dashboard take effect within ≤60 seconds.
- No changes to the bot codebase are required.
- No Express server or API is added to the bot.

## GuildConfiguration Schema Reference

```typescript
{
  guildId: string; // unique, required

  // Suggestions
  suggestionChannelIds: string[];
  suggestionCooldownMs: number; // default: 0

  // Minecraft
  pingEnabled: boolean; // default: false
  mcServers: Array<{
    name: string;
    ip: string;
    alertChannelId: string;
    alertRoleId: string;
    alertPingMode: 'both' | 'online' | 'offline';
    lastOnlineStatus: boolean;
    lastStatusChangeAt: Date;
    liveEmbedChannelId: string;
    liveEmbedMessageId: string;
    liveEmbedMode: 'edit' | 'resend';
    peakPlayersToday: number;
    peakPlayersDate: string;
  }>;

  // XP
  xpIgnoredChannelIds: string[];
  xpLevelUpChannelId: string;
  xpDisableLevelUpMessages: boolean;
  levelRoles: Array<{ level: number; roleId: string }>;

  // Welcome / Goodbye
  welcomeChannelId: string;
  welcomeMessage: string;
  goodbyeMessage: string;
  welcomeEmbed: boolean;
  welcomeColor: number; // hex, default: 0x00AA00
  goodbyeColor: number; // hex, default: 0xFF0000
  autoRoleIds: string[];

  // Mod Log
  modLogChannelId: string;
}
```

## Verification Checklist

- [ ] `npm run build` passes with zero TypeScript errors
- [ ] Login flow: visit `/login` → Discord OAuth → redirects to `/guilds` with correct guild list
- [ ] Only guilds where user is Administrator AND bot is present are shown
- [ ] Save a suggestion channel → verify update in MongoDB → bot uses it within 60s
- [ ] Non-admin user accessing another guild's config → 403 from API
- [ ] Invalid input (e.g. Minecraft server name with spaces) → rejected by Zod before DB write
- [ ] All 5 config sections load and save correctly
- [ ] Vercel deployment succeeds and is accessible at the configured domain

## Prerequisites

1. **Discord OAuth2 Application** — same app as the bot or a new one; needs `identify` + `guilds` scopes enabled and the Vercel redirect URI added
2. **Bot token** as env var on Vercel — used server-side only to fetch guild channels/roles (the bot is already in those guilds, so no additional permissions needed)
3. **MongoDB network access** — ensure the Atlas cluster allows connections from Vercel's IP range (or use `0.0.0.0/0` if already configured)
